Suppose you want to use the Wilcoxon rank sum test to detect a shift in distribution 1 to the right of distribution 2 based on samples of size  n1=6
  and  n2=8
 . Should you use  T1
  or  Tâˆ—1
  as the test statistic?
When using the Wilcoxon rank sum test to compare two samples, the test statistic depends on the sample size and whether or not the two samples have the same number of observations.

When the sample sizes are equal, the test statistic T and T* are equivalent and can be used interchangeably. However, when the sample sizes are unequal, T* is typically used instead of T to account for the unequal sample sizes.

In this case, since the sample sizes are different (n1=6 and n2=8), you should use T* as the test statistic in the Wilcoxon rank sum test.





